## Start
@node Start "Start"

When  you  need  move  around different menus, you press Next and Back
(explaining this is really difficult !)

In the first menu you get some commands...


[New]    It will erase all files previously loaded... 

[Load]   Program will load a datafile, it's ASCII so you can model it
         into  Doroty  or  build  it yourself...  I suggest to use the
         program also for autodiagnostic of errors

[Quit]   Do you really need some explanation about this ?

[Save]   After an editing you can save in an ASCII file your structure

[Info]   It opens a window with all you always wanted to know, (And you
         never try to ask...)

[Solve]  It  takes you to last menu.  It is useful if your datafile is
         ready and just loaded...


@endnode


## Junctions
@node Junctions "Junctions"

In the second menu you enter the number of junctions and poles.

But  you  can  change  this every time you need, and a special control
helps you to give an isostatic number of poles (and you get junctions)
or viceversa.

@endnode



## Coordinates
@node Coordinates "Coordinates"


In the third menu

We  find 2 botton, ---> means one unity plus, and <--- means one unity
minus,  for example you choose junction 4 and then you got junction 3.
You'll find the same then with poles in fourth menu.

Note  that  cycle  is closed, so if you are to last junction like e.g.
5,  and  push --> then you'll start again from 1!  It's easy, or not ?
When you choose a junction you can change its coordinates X and Y, and
Doroty  makes  a  new redrawing of picture in scale !  (great Doroty!)
Your axes are in your screen as in the picture below.



      ^  Y axis                 Example 
      |                                
      |                           
      |     ________
      |    /"  /"  /"
      |   /__"/__"/__"
      |__________________>   X axis
                        



@endnode

## Poles
@node Poles "Poles"

Now you can choose your poles and its first and second junctions.
All junctions are numbered, so you can't mistake... Or not ? :(

@endnode


## Bounds
@node Bounds "Bounds"


In  the  fifth screen (or bar or menu or anything else you prefer) you
can  choose  where  to put your bonds, Horizontal or Vertical, in your
favourite  junctions.   Move  your  cursor  with  -->  and <-- on your
junction and press Hori or Vert to insert or remove a bonds.

Every  bond  is  a  degree  of  freedom  in the frame, I don't know if
anglosaxon  technical literature calls them, but in graphical text you
find this picture:

  
   ||
   ||
   ||
   /\
  /__\    1 degree of freedom is blocked in vertical direction
 ()  ()


   The same picture is true in Horizontal direction   
   
          --> ======<|  e.g. a horizontal bond

  
Be  careful!  The number of bounds can't be less than 3, or you've got
an ipostatic structure, and the must be 2 Vert and one Horiz, or it is
a labile structure, and Doroty goes boom!

@endnode

## Loads
@node Loads "Loads"

In the sixth menu you can charge with all your Vertical and Horizontal
forces  the structure, only on your junctions.  You must put the value
of  two  component,  Vertical  and  Horizontal for every force.  Every
junction  can  be  loaded with a force.  The sign of vertical force is
positive  if  the  force  is pointed down, and for vertical if it goes
from left to right, just like axes horizontal coordinates.

@endnode

## Solve
@node Solve "Solve"

In  the  last  menu  you can see from screen all stress value on every
single poles and all reactions too...

Look  out!  Just for an easy reading all value are rounded to integer,
but in output file they are written with max precision.

Then you can send them with amigados on printer from a file built with
(Disk) command and also with the picture (Print) of structure, printed
on paper directly from Doroty.

@endnode
